There are two methods to read a single character from standard input. One is using a function like getch(), as you have seen. The other one is using a loop, that reads one character at a time from the input and puts it in a buffer, until it reaches the end of line.
The first method is simpler to use, but not portable.

The second method requires some boilerplate code to read and handle the buffer (e.g. std::stringstream), but it is portable and reliable.
Here are two simple examples for reading a single character from standard input:
```c++
// read one char and return it, not portable
char getch() {
    // Read a character and return it. If the input was EOF, returns 0.
    char ch = _getch();
    return ch;
}
// read one char and return it, portable (in C++14)
char getch(std::stringstream& ss) {
    // Read a character and put it in the buffer (ss). If the input was EOF, returns 0.
    char ch = _getch();
    if (ch == 0xff) { // end of file or error on Windows
        throw std::system_error(INVALID_FILE_ERROR, std::system_category()); // NOLINT(cppcoreguidelines-pro-type-info-operators)
    } else {
        ss << ch; // append to buffer ss if not EOF or error on Windows
    }
    return ch; // return the character read from buffer ss if not EOF or error on Windows (else do nothing)
}
```

